<DOC><DOCNO> AP890410-0255 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1915EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-GulfAir 1stLd-Writethru f0172 04-10 0275</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Gulf Air, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0172,0278</SECOND><HEAD>Gulf Air To Buy Six Boeing, 12 Airbus Planes For $1 Billion</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2 grafs for 2nd graf pvs to CORRECT plane type to 767ssted 727s, ADD Boeing comment; PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `Gulf Ai...</HEAD><DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Gulf Air said Monday it will spend $1billion over the next five years to buy 18 aircraft from theEuropean consortium Airbus Industrie and the U.S. manuacturerBoeing Co.   Gulf Air spokesman Abdullah Abdel-Karim said the airliners willinclude 12 Airbus A-320s and six Boeing 767s. Abdel-Karim said thedeal was being made on an optional basis, allowing the airline todrop an order without ann liability to compensate the manufacturer.   A spokesman for Seattle-based Boeing said it has held talks withGulf Air about purchasing 767s, but declined to confirm the deal.   Gulf Air is owned by the governments of Bahrain, Qatar, Oman andAbu Dhabi. The announcement came one day after Gulf Air's board metin the Qatari capital of Doha.   Abdel-Karim said that the 18 new jets will be delivered between1990 and 1994. Gulf Air is currently spending $260 million as partof a modernization program involving the lease of four Boeing767-300s.   The airline last week secured a $208 million loan from 22international and regional banks to cover part of the modenization.It expects to cover the balance of $52 million with a similarcredit from Japanese institutions.   Abdel-Karim said that by June the airline will have nineTri-Stars, eight Boeing 737s and six Boeing 767-300s. The fleetwill increase to 40 to 42 aircraft by 1994, he added.</TEXT></DOC>